{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778773579,"nonce":"crRffTrxzn0Nn2U3uByFJ2NEjw0=","message":"Verified cs2019's `B_w` structure by reading their MATLAB code at ModelDB 258846 (`minmaxfc_pointMass.m` and `AugRobustControl.m`). Resolves the ambiguity flagged in comment `0fb812f`. Plus records a design decision about the 2 disturbance-mediator integrator states.\n\n\nThe disturbance matrix is:\n```matlab\n% minmaxfc_pointMass.m:115-116\nD = zeros(size(A));\nD(1:8,1:8) = eye(8);\n```\n\n`D` is `48├Ś48` overall, but only the top-left `8├Ś8` block is identity. The Riccati uses `D┬ĘD'` (line 144-146), which is block-diagonal with `I_8` top-left and zeros elsewhere. **Equivalent to `B_w = [I_8; 0_{40├Ś8}]` (a 48├Ś8 selector).**\n\nThe adversary's ╬Ą is 8-dimensional, entering only the current physical state. Lagged components evolve deterministically via the canonical block-shift augmented dynamics (`AugRobustControl.m:25-35`). The forward sim confirms: `currentX = Aest*currentX + B*u(i,:)' + D*wx + motorNoise + sdn;` (line 279) ŌĆö disturbance filtered through `D` before being added.\n\n**Bottom line: the cs2019 adversary does not \"reach back in time.\"** Physical intuition holds. Setup 2 from comment `0fb812f` is what cs2019 actually implements.\n\n\ncs2019's 8 physical state components (per the MATLAB code, lines 63-66):\n- 2 position (`x, y`)\n- 2 velocity (`vx, vy`)\n- 2 muscle/control force state (`fx, fy`, output of the first-order muscle filter)\n- 2 **disturbance-mediator states** (the MATLAB variable names suggest \"external force state\" but functionally they're integrators driven by ╬Ą that couple back into velocity)\n\nrlrmp's `cs_faithful_pointmass` (`src/rlrmp/analysis/hinf_riccati.py:468-498`) uses the same 8-state structure, naming the last two `[eps_x_int, eps_y_int]`. Confirmed via the docstring: \"adds two pure-integrator states `[eps_x_int, eps_y_int]` driven by the disturbance ╬Ą (rows 7,8 of A are zero). The integrators couple back into the velocity rows via `A[3,7]=A[4,8]=1`.\"\n\n\n- **╬Ż_╬Ą is rank-8, not identity** over the augmented state. The disturbance covariance is supported only on the current physical state; ╬│Ōü╗┬▓ in the Riccati does all the budget-tuning.\n- **Adversary is time-invariant** ŌĆö `D` doesn't change over time. ╬│ is optimised once per trial via a bisection loop (`minmaxfc_pointMass.m:134-168`).\n- **Motor noise + sensory noise are separate from the HŌł× disturbance** ŌĆö they appear only in the forward sim and Kalman update (`Oxi`, `Omega`, lines 211, 213), never in the Riccati. cs2019's HŌł× adversary is purely the additive ╬Ą on the physical 8 dims.\n- **`DA` term** (cs2019's structural-╬öA-like term, from their Eq 7's physical motivation, lines 69 and 278) is *also* confined to the physical block via the same `D` selector. So even their multiplicative-disturbance framing is operationally physical-only in the implementation. One more nail in the coffin of \"cs2019 used flavor-(b)\" ŌĆö their actual game is consistently flavor-(a) physical-only.\n\n\ncs2019's 2 disturbance-mediator states (whether named `ext_fx, ext_fy` in MATLAB or `eps_x_int, eps_y_int` in rlrmp) are NOT pure analytical convenience ŌĆö they low-pass-filter ╬Ą's path to velocity through one of the entry pathways. Without them, ╬Ą directly perturbs v╠ć; with them, ╬Ą accumulates in the integrator and drives v╠ć via A-coupling.\n\nHowever, rlrmp's own audit (Bug `9a0558e`, documented in `cs_faithful_pointmass`'s docstring) found that under `B_w = I_8` the worst-case adversary always finds a more efficient direct-velocity attack than going through the integrator pathway. **Result: the integrator columns are \"dynamically inert from the adversary's perspective\" ŌĆö they don't change `╬│*` or `K_phys` for the HŌł× game.** They still affect the closed-loop response shape but not the optimal-game solution.\n\nThis makes a clean experimental sequence available:\n\n1. **Step 1 ŌĆö Use integrators (cs2019-faithful)**. cs_faithful_pointmass on the 8-state including integrators. Riccati round-trip target derived from this. Establishes the cs2019-matched analytical reference.\n\n2. **Step 2 ŌĆö Drop integrators (cs2019-equivalent demonstration)**. Re-run the Riccati on the 6-state plant (no integrators). Show that the HŌł× game's solution (╬│*, K_phys, behavioural signature) is approximately preserved. This validates the audit finding empirically and licenses the next step.\n\n3. **Step 3 ŌĆö Proceed without integrators in feedbax**. The trained-controller side uses a standard 6-state feedbax point-mass plant with ╬Ą injected directly into the velocity-dot equation. No augmented mediator states needed in feedbax. Implementation work in feedbax is correspondingly cleaner ŌĆö the new `FullStateAdditivePerturb` intervenor writes ╬Ą to the 6 physical state components, period.\n\nThis avoids dragging cs2019's analytical-convenience integrators into feedbax's plant model, while still anchoring the trained-controller's game to the cs2019 analytical reference via the step 1ŌåÆ2 equivalence demonstration.\n\n\n- The state-map regression test for `FullStateAdditivePerturb` (Codex blocker from round 2) becomes trivial under the 6-state target: one ╬Ą basis vector ŌåÆ one of 6 physical state coordinates changed, current step only, no delay-buffer or integrator-state mutation hooks needed.\n- The Riccati equivalence demonstration (step 2 above) becomes part of Phase 0.5 analytical-target materialisation ŌĆö produce both the 8-state and 6-state Riccati targets, compare, log the difference, declare the 6-state target the contract going forward.\n- The delay-handling question (comment `0fb812f`'s setup 1 / setup 2 choice) is unchanged: still default to 50ms delay-augmented for the primary gate, no-delay as supplementary analysis.","files":null}]}